  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Imprisonment\n- Up to 10-20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Consecutive sentences possible for multiple counts\n\n2. Substantial Financial Penalties\n- Significant monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or double the value of the funds involved\n\n3. Asset Forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets connected to laundering activities\n- Property, bank accounts, and other financial instruments may be confiscated\n\n4. Additional Consequences\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty obtaining future financial opportunities\n- Permanent criminal record\n\n5. Civil Penalties\n- Potential civil lawsuits\n- Additional financial sanctions\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like the amount of money involved, number of transactions, and specific circumstances of the offense. Sentencing is typically determined under federal sentencing guidelines.\n\nThese penalties are enforced primarily by agencies like the Department of Justice, FBI, and IRS Criminal Investigation Division.\n\nNote: This is general information about federal money laundering penalties and should not be considered legal advice. Specific cases can vary significantly.",
